




TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Lagrangian Relaxation Method for Solving Integer Programming Problems
AU  - Fisher, Marshall L.
Y1  - 1981/01/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.27.1.1
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.27.1.1
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1
EP  - 18
VL  - 27
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - One of the most computationally useful ideas of the 1970s is the observation that many hard integer programming problems can be viewed as easy problems complicated by a relatively small set of side constraints. Dualizing the side constraints produces a Lagrangian problem that is easy to solve and whose optimal value is a lower bound (for minimization problems) on the optimal value of the original problem. The Lagrangian problem can thus be used in place of a linear programming relaxation to provide bounds in a branch and bound algorithm. This approach has led to dramatically improved algorithms for a number of important problems in the areas of routing, location, scheduling, assignment and set covering. This paper is a review of Lagrangian relaxation based on what has been learned in the last decade.
AB  - One of the most computationally useful ideas of the 1970s is the observation that many hard integer programming problems can be viewed as easy problems complicated by a relatively small set of side constraints. Dualizing the side constraints produces a Lagrangian problem that is easy to solve and whose optimal value is a lower bound (for minimization problems) on the optimal value of the original problem. The Lagrangian problem can thus be used in place of a linear programming relaxation to provide bounds in a branch and bound algorithm. This approach has led to dramatically improved algorithms for a number of important problems in the areas of routing, location, scheduling, assignment and set covering. This paper is a review of Lagrangian relaxation based on what has been learned in the last decade.
